---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="About" activeNav="about">
  <article>
    <h1 class="about-title">About</h1>
    <div class="about-title-rule">
      <span>&sect;</span>
      <span class="line"></span>
    </div>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        I'm Stan Angeloff — CTO by day, tinkerer by heart. Based in Sofia,
        Bulgaria. I run the tech at <a href="https://www.luup.com/">Luup</a>. This
        blog is my personal space for thoughts, rants &amp; research.
      </p>

      <h2><span class="accent">&#9670;</span>What I'm up to (2025&mdash;)</h2>
      <p>
        Most of my free time goes into <a
          href="https://github.com/Flemma-Dev/flemma.nvim">Flemma</a>
        &mdash; a low-level AI workspace that runs inside Neovim. Not a wrapper, the actual
        thing: streaming APIs, tool execution, prompt pipelines, talking to Anthropic,
        OpenAI and Google directly. I built it because I needed it for work &mdash; PRDs,
        statements of work, R&amp;D spikes, client documentation. Every feature exists
        because a real problem demanded it.
      </p>
      <p>
        The core belief: models come and go, but the workspace you build around
        them is yours. Go one level lower than you think you need to. Write your
        own agents, wire up your own tool execution, parse your own streaming
        responses. The best way to understand AI tooling is to build it yourself.
      </p>
      <p>
        I'm also experimenting with <a href="https://github.com/Flemma-Dev/voxize"
          >Voxize</a>, a voice-to-text tool for Linux/Wayland &mdash; my daily driver for
        AI-assisted coding instead of reaching for the keyboard.
      </p>

      <h2><span class="accent">&#9670;</span>Technical background</h2>
      <p>
        I've been at this for over two decades, touching just about everything
        along the way. Some highlights from the archives:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>CoffeeScript</strong> &mdash; used to be a top 10 contributor to <a
            href="https://github.com/jashkenas/coffeescript/graphs/contributors"
            >jashkenas/coffeescript</a> (now sitting at #9, but who's counting)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Ruby</strong> &mdash; built <a
            href="https://github.com/StanAngeloff/compass-magick"
            >compass-magick</a> and <a href="https://github.com/StanAngeloff/compass-canvas"
            >compass-canvas</a>, dynamic image generation in pure Sass
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>PHP</strong> &mdash; created <a
            href="https://github.com/StanAngeloff/php.vim">php.vim</a>,
          the community-standard Vim syntax for PHP (473+ stars)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>JavaScript</strong> &mdash; built <a
            href="https://github.com/StanAngeloff/zoey">Zoey</a>,
          a lightweight mobile app framework, and <a
            href="https://github.com/StanAngeloff/lotte">Lotte</a>,
          headless browser testing with PhantomJS before Puppeteer existed
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Shell &amp; terminal</strong> &mdash; a big believer in open, free, terminal-based
          tools. Built <a
            href="https://github.com/StanAngeloff/vagrant-shell-scripts"
            >vagrant-shell-scripts</a> back when provisioning VMs was the thing to do
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>GitOps</strong> &mdash; managed all my PCs with <a
            href="https://github.com/StanAngeloff/longitude">Ansible</a> for years, even <a
            href="https://github.com/RogueDudes/automate-all-the-things"
            >gave a talk about it</a> back when Ansible was the underdog. Now I run <a
            href="https://github.com/StanAngeloff/nix-meridian">NixOS</a>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        TypeScript, Node.js, and whatever else the job demands &mdash; I've never been
        one to stick to a single stack.
      </p>

      <h2><span class="accent">&#9670;</span>The honest bit</h2>
      <p>
        As you can tell, most of those projects are pretty old. I haven't been as
        active in the OSS community as I'd like &mdash; but I'm still here, still
        tinkering, and Flemma is where that energy goes now.
      </p>

      <p>
        You can find me on <a href="https://github.com/StanAngeloff">GitHub</a><span style="color:var(--ink-faint);margin:0 8px">&middot;</span><a
          href="https://news.ycombinator.com/user?id=StanAngeloff">Hacker News</a><span style="color:var(--ink-faint);margin:0 8px">&middot;</span><a
          href="https://mastodon.social/@stanangeloff" rel="me">Mastodon</a><span style="color:var(--ink-faint);margin:0 8px">&middot;</span><a
          href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/stanangeloff/">LinkedIn</a><span style="color:var(--ink-faint);margin:0 8px">&middot;</span><a
          href="https://x.com/StanAngeloff">X</a>
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="end-mark">&sect;</div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
